<review>I believe that Passages Malibu is a one-of-kind treatment facility. It‚Äôs located so close to the ocean that you can hear the waves crashing down onto the beach.

The staff are kind and caring and try their best to accommodate client needs. The rooms are clean, the property is well maintained and food is delicious. If you have any sort of allergy (Food, environmental, medication), they can work around it. The staff will often go on Store Runs if you need anything from a Ralph‚Äôs or CVS.

They allow clients to leave the property upon discretion of administration. There are activities such as: Tennis, Goat Yoga, Beach Walks, Outings to Target, Bowling, Movies, In-N-Out, etc. Clients are allowed to order food if they choose to and are allowed to ship packages to themselves.

You‚Äôre absolutely allowed to bring and buy things to make you feel more at home, just as long as you‚Äôre abiding by the set guidelines that are explained upon admission.

There is WiFi throughout the property so that you can stay in contact with your friends and families (If you choose to). They are open to allowing a client to go off of the property to practice the coping skills that they have learned.

The main thing I can say is that it is really up to the person that comes here. You must be open and willing to put in the energy and work to overcome the struggle.<//review><Pics>None<//Pics>< resp>

0x80e818d2edd29e2d:0x1b33cb0e688e8a3d< /Gmap_id>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<response>None<//response><review>I had never been to inpatient treatment before and was admitted with a dual diagnosis situation.  I had a fairly serious medical condition and as a result began heavily self medicating.  I have heard about lots of others experiences going to "rehab" and while I don't want to dis any treatment modality, because if it works for you then great, but knowing my personality type I did not want to go anywhere AA/NA was the focus.

Passages treated me as an individual and did not use a "cookie cutter" approach to its treatment paradigm.  Also, I was very opposed to going anywhere which group therapy was part of the program.  Passages was the closest to meeting those two criteria.  My therapy consisted of approximately 80% one on one sessions and the balance were in small groups.  In hindsight, some of my group sessions were  of my favorites. In part the small groups  gave my brain a chance to rest from intensive one on one therapy, but it afforded me an opportunity to get to know the other clients and what they were going through.  This proved to be especially valuable when during off hours and interacting in the milieu I grew a bond with several of the other clients who I will consider friends for life.

I am sure that every type of group living a treatment situation has drama and issues - just like life and treatment was no different.  However, if there ever was an issue or concern they were heard immediately.  I have to say that everyone from the housekeeping and ground staff to the therapists, administration  and even the entire extended Prentiss family, Chris, Lynn, Pax and Joe were always warm, engaging and really took a personal interest in getting to know me.

No one day at Passages was the same.  After detoxing and getting in a routine, Passages made tremendous strides to assist me in re-engaging with reality for lack of a better word. I learned so much about myself I feel like I could write on for days about my experience.  Having put myself through so much trauma by self medicating and feeling shell shocked when I arrived, I can say that gratitude is one of the words I would use in describing my experience at Passages.

From a counseling perspective, I had a primary pscho-therapist, an addiction counselor, a family therapist, a hypnotherapist, a life coach, massage therapist, an acupuncturist, an adventure therapy counselor and an art therapy counselor.  My day started around 8 am for breakfast and depending on the day would have counseling from 8 am until noon, or 9 am until noon, each session lasting one hour and then four more one hour sessions after lunch.  That was Monday - Friday.   One day I could have a heavy psychotherapy session from 10-11 am and then a session with my private trainer from 11-12 which may have been a workout at its onsite fitness center, or a power walk on the beach.  Again, no one day was ever the same.  Things like equine therapy and art therapy were enjoyable but always had a therapeutic component and it worked very well.

There were many optional activities on the weekends as you "leveled up" through the program. As you progress through the program you also are allowed more freedom.  At first when you get there, at least for me, I was pretty exhausted.  But as time went on, I started doing the early morning beach walks, which are optional, and a small group would be driven a couple miles up the road to Zuma beach, and some days I would walk on the beach and other days I would sit and stare at the ocean and contemplate life and try to absorb the view.  The whole approach at Passages is to help you transcend back to a place where being high or drunk is not your reality or where you reside, instead bring you back to residing where being substance free is your normal natural zone.

Passages was amazing for me - and regardless of where u go ‚Äì and if you need help - go somewhere - get help - it will be the best choice you ever make !!! i give passages all five stars!<//review>< UserId.>

<userid>113569787594756167759<//userid><user_name>JS Dickey</user_name><Date>1554414531467< /Date><Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
I had never been to inpatient treatment before and was admitted with a dual diagnosis situation.  I had a fairly serious medical condition and as a result began heavily self medicating.  I have heard about lots of others experiences going to "rehab" and while I don't want to dis any treatment modality, because if it works for you then great, but knowing my personality type I did not want to go anywhere AA/NA was the focus.

Passages treated me as an individual and did not use a "cookie cutter" approach to its treatment paradigm.  Also, I was very opposed to going anywhere which group therapy was part of the program.  Passages was the closest to meeting those two criteria.  My therapy consisted of approximately 80% one on one sessions and the balance were in small groups.  In hindsight, some of my group sessions were  of my favorites. In part the small groups  gave my brain a chance to rest from intensive one on one therapy, but it afforded me an opportunity to get to know the other clients and what they were going through.  This proved to be especially valuable when during off hours and interacting in the milieu I grew a bond with several of the other clients who I will consider friends for life.

I am sure that every type of group living a treatment situation has drama and issues - just like life and treatment was no different.  However, if there ever was an issue or concern they were heard immediately.  I have to say that everyone from the housekeeping and ground staff to the therapists, administration  and even the entire extended Prentiss family, Chris, Lynn, Pax and Joe were always warm, engaging and really took a personal interest in getting to know me.

No one day at Passages was the same.  After detoxing and getting in a routine, Passages made tremendous strides to assist me in re-engaging with reality for lack of a better word. I learned so much about myself I feel like I could write on for days about my experience.  Having put myself through so much trauma by self medicating and feeling shell shocked when I arrived, I can say that gratitude is one of the words I would use in describing my experience at Passages.

From a counseling perspective, I had a primary pscho-therapist, an addiction counselor, a family therapist, a hypnotherapist, a life coach, massage therapist, an acupuncturist, an adventure therapy counselor and an art therapy counselor.  My day started around 8 am for breakfast and depending on the day would have counseling from 8 am until noon, or 9 am until noon, each session lasting one hour and then four more one hour sessions after lunch.  That was Monday - Friday.   One day I could have a heavy psychotherapy session from 10-11 am and then a session with my private trainer from 11-12 which may have been a workout at its onsite fitness center, or a power walk on the beach.  Again, no one day was ever the same.  Things like equine therapy and art therapy were enjoyable but always had a therapeutic component and it worked very well.

There were many optional activities on the weekends as you "leveled up" through the program. As you progress through the program you also are allowed more freedom.  At first when you get there, at least for me, I was pretty exhausted.  But as time went on, I started doing the early morning beach walks, which are optional, and a small group would be driven a couple miles up the road to Zuma beach, and some days I would walk on the beach and other days I would sit and stare at the ocean and contemplate life and try to absorb the view.  The whole approach at Passages is to help you transcend back to a place where being high or drunk is not your reality or where you reside, instead bring you back to residing where being substance free is your normal natural zone.

Passages was amazing for me - and regardless of where u go ‚Äì and if you need help - go somewhere - get help - it will be the best choice you ever make !!! i give passages all five stars!<//review>

<text>I just want to say that this facility is phenomenal and is responsible for bringing one of my best friends back to healthy life.  Writing a review is new to me, so excuse me for lack of detail or for not being super specific but I learned about the things that go on there after the fact and I agree with the methodology full on, so I'll try and list some things and my own opinion. I don't know much about other facilities; I had friends go to some in High School, but I never heard any details. I did however hear about a few things that I feel set it apart from the others. One being that they have several counselors/therapists that meet with their patients during the week, that the facility/living quarters itself is absolutely beautiful, and that there are many physical activities to help patients appreciate what normal life should be about. There are various forms of physically gratifying and mental treatment that go on constantly throughout the day, like acupuncture, hiking, yoga, sound therapy, and many others. These are all normal key things that you and I might do to decompress, (I'm a musician so sound therapy is my life,) but an addict most likely does not and doesn't know how to relieve themselves like a normal person. It's also in Malibu, which is known for it's beautiful scenery/beaches/trails etc and they are certainly taking advantage of that, as they should.  I'm not an addict and don't have a history with addiction, but I do in my family, and it has DESTROYED one half of it. I do know that in order for someone to recover from something that intense you would definitely need to be pulled out completely from those situations and surroundings that encourage that behavior, your dependency, and the neglect for the reasons why you're actually taking drugs in the first place. Addicts need an area where they can whole heartedly, and not just temporarily put addiction to the side, and to be reintroduced to ALL the elements/ and positivity of normal healthy life. I certainly feel like this place is one of the best places to take care of that directly, and I have living proof. This review is the best way I can repay them. Thank you.< /text>< pictures>

< Text>
I struggled and battled with addiction for most of my life.  I tried many different ways and variations to get and stay sober.  While I did manage to maintain long periods of sobriety there was always something missing.  Always that void.  I couldn‚Äôt get passed that place where I would face and work on my core issues and deal with me.  Finally at the end of my rope, more literally than you can imagine, I was sitting on my couch and the Passages commercial came on.  I don‚Äôt know how or why but before I knew what was happening the phone was in my hand and ringing.  That call would change my life.
I was connected to a woman named Jennifer.  I told her ‚ÄúI think I need to come there‚Äù and she softly replied ‚Äúoh sweetie if you are calling me I think you need to come here as well‚Äù.  Over the next few days Jennifer and Michael were not only ‚Äúadmissions people‚Äù they were kind caring friends that stayed in contact with me until I was ready to come in.  I truly was hopeless.  Life had become too much living and battling with addiction.  I had lost my family and everyone including myself had given up on me.
Upon entering Passages I was truly amazed at how they made me feel.  It was not entering a rehab or treatment center.  They made me feel as if I was home. Everyone from the nursing staff, kitchen staff, receptionists, therapists, client supervisors and even the owners Pax and Chris immediately knew my name, who I was, why I was there and that there was hope.  The scheduling and therapy sessions you are given are very intense and there is no game playing.  Getting to the core of your issues is their goal and they get there quickly.  The program is very busy and the amount of work, time and energy they put into you is like nothing I have ever seen.  After many, many years of trying the conventional therapy systems and 12 step programs and never reaching the levels of work or learning and dealing with my issues as well as the support I was getting from Passages not only did I find a treatment center I became part of a family and support group I never thought I would have.  Upon my discharge I was setup with a therapist in my area, which is on the other side of the country, and an aftercare plan.  I was also given an aftercare coordinator and to this day get a couple of emails a month checking on my progress and making sure any needs I have that Passages can help me with are met.
Now it has been a few years and I can say I have a freedom today I never thought imaginable.  I still practice the things I learned at Passages.  I still am in communication with the staff that helped me and continues to help me.  Never did I or do I feel like a number or just another client.  I mattered and still matter.  Many of the folks I went thru the program with are happy, healthy,  sober and I am still in contact with.  We get together.  We see each other.  We skype regularly and are involved in each other‚Äôs lives and recovery.  I am part of a family and one I am proud to be.  All they say the offer they do and so much more IF you want it and are willing to do the work.  God Bless Passages and everyone there that puts so much into helping people and changing people‚Äôs lives.  It sure has mine.<//Text>
<name>Richard Santaniello<//name></record>

<text>Open table reservations were easy, required a credit card in advance but this place was well worth it. Great for table conversation, couples or groups, and a fun open atmosphere. Staff were on-point with the team approach, perfect balance of attention and not pestering. $25 corkage which is reasonable although they do have a great bottle selection there. Cocktails were artfully prepared and a must try! Sweet potato pakoras to start were good small bites to share, the yogurt sauce made them everything they were. Hamachi crudo might as well be their signature dish. Lobster rissotto was absolutely delicious and a must order if on the menu. Friend got scallops which were out of this world too. Pork belly was also remarkable but didn't compare to our seafood dishes. Pasta didn't do anything for us, but wasn't bad. Our carrot cake desert was tasty but had an artful deconstruction flair to it that left us leaving wanting something more (house made ice cream however was a huge highlight). $370 after tip for 4 people each having multiple courses, cocktails and our own bottle (corkage) was a good value in our eyes and if you've read this far you should just book a table and go! :)<//text><user_id>114690080820591679489<//user_id>< Pics>

0x808506670e04109d:0x86fa7c6c29f90d61<//Gmap_id>
< username>
Sherry Li<//username>
<rate>4<//rate>< review>
Our first meal in Napa post-Covid was at Torc. We got a table in the back patio. It was a large patio with only 4 tables, situated pretty far apart from each other. All of the staff were wearing masks and gloves. They even provided envelopes to put our masks in. Menus were one use, but silverware was not, but I'm sure they were properly cleaned and sanitized.

The menu is very shareable. For apps, we got the iberico and bread. The ham was very good and the bread was a good call because the ham only came with 2 slices of crostini. The bread was amazing. Each order comes with four THICK slices: rosemary, sourdough, levain, and walnut (I think), and enough butter to cover all the surface area and then some.

For mains, we both got truffle dishes because it's truffle season. The grilled cheese was amazing. But after the ham and bread, I had trouble finishing it because it was so rich. Good problem to have, I supposed. The rigatoni with truffle was also very good. It was a very carb-heavy meal.

For dessert, we went with the chocolate tart and the citrus sorbet. The tart was decadent and very chocolatey. The sorbet was surprisingly rich for a sorbet. I think they added some olive oil.

All in all, it was a delicious (and expensive) meal.<//review>

< Review>
The food, drinks, and ambiance at Torc are unmatched in Napa. The places is something of an underrated gem of the area. The menu changes seasonally, but never fails to impress. The drinks are varied, with takes on classic cocktails, unique combinations, and a solid wine list. While the service has been up and down, overall Torc still earns 5 stars.</Review>

<user_id>108554285581933801096< /user_id><username>Max Calderon<//username>< Date>
1496516596850<//Date>
< rating>
5<//rating>
< Review>
Awesome! Girlfriend and I went here for a birthday dinner - nothing short of five stars. The description is perfect, the place is 'loud' and has music - but tastefully in a way it's hard to put your finger on. It isn't a bar, and if you weren't distracted by the art, your cocktails, wine, or food, you might not notice the constant hum and energy at all.

Service was stellar. Our gal wasn't overbearing. She would come by the table and leave us space when it was obvious we didn't need anything, and gave great recommendations. She went as far as getting a recipe of the digestif we ordered and have it written down for us.

Food was great. Perfectly large portions, with great balance in sauce, protein vegetables, other.. And the drinks were great.

Born in the bay, now in Portland, and with a foodie for a girlfriend- we have a taste for good food, and this is some some the best food I've had. We didn't expect to walk out of here cheap, but for half a dozen drinks, two entrees, some appetizers and desert and the quality of food and service, ~$250 seemed very appropriate.

It's obvious that this place was designed with a high amount of attention and experience. I can't help but highly recommend this place. If there's time between tastings, it's definitely on my next Napa itinerary.< /Review>

<userid>102823187167747198572<//userid>< name>
Ketan Vohora< /name>
< Time>
1504675413336< /Time>
<rating>1</rating>< review>
We were very excited to try this place as it was our first wedding anniversary so we made a reso well in advance. To start, we were seated in the worst possible spot in the restaurant - a table right near the door that was meant for four even though we were a party of two. We ordered the ribeye steak for two, which we were told it would take 40 mins to prepare. As we knew it would be a while we ordered a soup to start. The soup was good but the server took our menu away even though we asked her to leave it so we can order something else if we needed. Instead she took it away and we had to sit around for almost 30 mins trying to get her attention or waiting for her to come by to check on us. What was irritating was that the price of food here was higher than any restaurant we'd been at since we started our trip but the food we ordered (when it finally arrived) was nothing special.

The big takeaway - the server and the service we received was too poor for the price point that this place charges. The quality of the food is not as great as other places in Napa that we tried. I recommend trying other places!< /review>

< Text>
I had an excellent experience at The People‚Äôs Barbershop on Townsend Street in downtown San Francisco (South of Market). The People‚Äôs Barbershop has several locations in the Bay Area (San Francisco and Oakland). The shop is modern, clean, well lite, and has qualified and talented barbers.   Luckily, personal services have been deemed safe in the city, and like so many, I was in need of a haircut. The People‚Äôs Barbershop takes walk-in and appointments, but, I highly recommend making an appointment online. This can be easily done on their website, just pick the location and you can pick the barber and the service needed. Most appointments are in 30 - 45 minute increments based on the service you need. One of the best features about the site is that you can see a picture of the barber, select a service and see their professional Instagram page. This is a clutch feature, especially if you‚Äôre getting your haircut for the first time, by a new barber, which was my experience. I got a cut from Cristian and it was excellent. He is professional, talented, and personable. I highly recommend the brand and if you‚Äôre in need of a good barber, schedule an appointment with him.<//Text>

< text>
Dr Ardesh is wonderful.  He is passionate about his work and takes a genuine interest in his patients.  He removed a large cyst on the side of my head just inside my hairline.  He first took as much time as I needed to explain and answer questions about the procedure and recovery.  His gentle and caring demeanor kept me relaxed and calm throughout the procedure.  The surgery was done in his office with a local anesthetic, so I was awake the entire time.  During surgery he would periodically let me know what he was doing and what it might feel like, which I appreciated very much.  He also asked a few conversational questions, probably to assess how I was feeling and to distract my attention from what he was doing.  It worked and I felt calm and relaxed through the entire procedure.

That evening, while relaxing at home, I received a phone call from Dr. Ardesh just checking in to see how I was doing and if I had any questions or concerns.  Wow, when was the last time a doctor called to check on you?!  We were going into a weekend and he let me know that I should never hesitate to call or text him about any concerns I might have.  It has been two weeks since the surgery and I am healing very nicely.

I have the ultimate respect for and trust in Dr. Ardesh and highly recommend him.< /text>

<Text>I was suffering from an ingrown sebaceous cyst on my cheek for almost 3 years. These types of unsightly cysts are fairly common for males of African descent and men of color. < text>
I came in to see Dr. A in the hopes of fixing my deviated septum once and for all. I was about 10 months away from my wedding day and I was sick of not being able to breath properly. I had a septoplasty a couple years ago which was performed by a different surgeon. It never worked and even made my breathing worse.

I thought the fix would be very straight forward: revision septoplasty. Dr. A took a look at my nose and let me know that it would be a bit more complex and that he would need to perform a septorhinoplasty with turbinate reduction. He was so thoughtful and confident in his decision process. Doctors that I had seen before were much more ‚Äúonce-size-fits-all‚Äù with their solutions and barely took the time to explore my complex situation.

Dr. A explained what to expect very thoroughly and was happy to answer all of my questions. He also made sure not to sugar coat anything. The surgery would be long and the recovery would be a lot harder than the septoplasty. He also warned me that while I wouldn‚Äôt be 100% healed by my wedding day, I would be extremely close. I could tell that he wanted me to be as thoughtful and well informed as possible before committing to such a big thing.

Once I decided to go for it, he made sure he was able to give me a closer date to start the process with my wedding in mind. The surgery was long and went late into the night. Dr. A did exactly what he said he would: take as much time as he needed to get the job done right. Of course I was very loopy after the surgery so he only talked to my family. But the next morning he called me at 7:00 am to check in. This is when I knew I had the best, most caring doctor working with me.

Through my recovery, Dr. A  handled my post op appointments with great care. He gave me his personal number to use any time I had questions or concerns. One Sunday I shot him a text with an issue I was having with my right passage way. I was experiencing some pain and wanted to check to see if everything was okay. He immediately called me and eased my fears and told me to come in first thing the next day just to make sure everything was okay. After taking a look, everything was fine. He gave me a quick cleaning and sent me on my way with a huge sense of relief that I was healing properly.

He continued to be responsive to any other questions I had. While my nose is still in the early stages of healing, I am already experiencing such a huge improvement in my breathing. I am also incredibly happy with the appearance of my nose. It looks so natural and I still look like me. Dr. A is the best doctor I‚Äôve ever worked with. I‚Äôm not sure how I got so lucky. I highly encourage anyone who is reading this to let him help you the way he helped me.</text>

<Text>There is only one word to describe Dr. Ardeshirpour, BRILLIANT!!!

I met Dr. Ardeshirpour in January of 2017 due to the concern of difficulty breathing through my nose and a saddle nasal deformity, which was the result of a 15-year boxing career. Over this period of time I sustained multiple nasal injuries and broke my nose on three separate occasions. I used to lay in bed for hours because of the inability to breathe through my nose especially when I laid down on my back, and I would frequently toss and turn as result and wake up feeling sluggish and fatigued. When I met Dr. Ardeshirpour he immediately knew I couldn‚Äôt breathe through my nose due to the noticeable nasal collapse I had. He then proceeded with his detailed exam of my nose, looking inside with a scope and finding a severely deviated nasal septum that was also buckled. He spent an hour of his time answering all of my questions and concerns and any other options that were available. He brilliantly explained that in order to improve my nasal breathing, he would first need to fix the structure of my external nose and the septum on the inside so that the function of my nose would improve. Meaning, I would need a rhinoplasty to fix the outside structure in addition to a septoplasty to fix the inside structure so I can improve air flow, thus breathe through my nose.

Two months later, I followed through with the surgery (a complex functional septorhinoplasty) and had a great postoperative recovery. After my first week out from surgery, Dr. Ardeshirpour removed my nasal cast and nasal splints and for the first time in years I was able to breathe through both sides of my nose. It was a breath of fresh air and life changing for me. The weeks and months to follow were filled with me waking up feeling well rested and energized as well as having a great looking nose that actually works. I can breathe!!

It has been 1 year and 4 months since my surgery with Dr. Ardesh and let me tell you, it was the best decision I have ever made, to trust him with my nose and let him transform a battered nose into an amazing natural appearing nose. Thank you Dr. Ardeshirpour!! If you want an excellent doctor who is going to be honest with you and do the right thing for you, then Dr. Ardeshirpour is the doc for you.</Text>< pictures>
